responded: The root cause of the use-after-free is in `flush_unmatched`:

```c
758|     while (pObj->currentProfilerContext) {
759|         ProfilerContext *pContext = pObj->currentProfilerContext;
760|         ProfilerEntry *profEntry= pContext->ctxEntry;
761|         if (profEntry)
762|             Stop(pObj, pContext, profEntry);
763|         else
764|             pObj->currentProfilerContext = pContext->previous;
765|         if (pContext)
766|             PyMem_Free(pContext);
767|     }
```

Here, `Stop()` will set `pObj->currentProfilerContext = self->previous;` (where `self` is `pContext`). But after `Stop()`, `pObj->currentProfilerContext` is now `pContext->previous`, but the loop frees `pContext` (which is still the pointer it saved at the start of the loop), not the new value. On the next iteration, `pObj->currentProfilerContext` will be a dangling pointer if the list is traversed incorrectly or reused.

**The correct sequence:**
- Save `pObj->currentProfilerContext` into `pContext`.
- Advance `pObj->currentProfilerContext` to the next before freeing `pContext`.

**Patch plan:**
- After `Stop()` or the `else`, always update `pObj->currentProfilerContext = pContext->previous;` before freeing `pContext`.
- Remove duplicate updates.

